{"$ambrosia":"aero:interactive:9417ac60-5f60-11ea-8e69-affb2224d7e8:*","$id":"10f1f990-44e0-11ed-8748-54d51869049c","$workspaceId":"7fff47c0-44d6-11ed-bcef-d5307f42495c","$projectId":"86cb0040-44df-11ed-8442-dbcbc27803ca","annotations":[],"configSchemaVersion":"/pluginGenericSchema/v1","config":{"stage":{"sections":[{"rows":[{"columns":[{"stageElements":[{"type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"heading-one","ref":"614633cd-20f3-4184-82d3-5a22132da3b6","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"22.2 Market Reaction to a Takeover","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]}},"config":{"cssClass":""},"ref":"98c53e1c-9b30-4108-92b1-ce912f652e79"},{"type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"54428457-7216-4643-94cb-f17fbab6e3eb","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"In most U.S. states, the law requires that when existing shareholders of a target firm are forced to sell their shares, they receive a fair value for their shares. Typically this concept is interpreted as the value exclusive of any value that arises because of the merger itself. For practical purposes, this principle translates into the share price prior to the merger. As a consequence, a bidder is unlikely to acquire a target company for less than its current market value. Instead, most acquirers pay a substantial ","marks":[]},{"data":{"ref":"dcadb0f1-b43c-41e1-9b7b-241804998bae","stage":{"ref":"11749a18-d6f9-431d-a5ae-a821c07c1c15","sections":[{"ref":"bd1a8611-c0b1-43fe-a0be-9e61e2fdf328","rows":[{"ref":"5b6eb90b-05fa-45b6-b5fa-22aaff59b233","columns":[{"ref":"09fb44ce-5322-4192-9a8c-1d163f6ef8f7","stageElements":[{"ref":"b9851ef2-53f0-4873-be0e-b3b737d4c1e0","type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"button","ref":"f1917f77-6eb0-4830-8877-4ca1b9c000fa","nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"cba50275-9bfe-4032-ab3b-ba0a51539083","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Paid by an acquirer in a takeover, it is the percentage difference between the acquisition price and the premerger price of a target firm.","marks":[]}],"data":{}}],"data":{}}]}}}]}]}]}]}},"nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"acquisition premium","marks":[{"type":"bold"}]}],"object":"inline","type":"key-term","ref":"8b217993-bbfb-4185-9189-2eecfce7e092"},{"object":"text","text":", which is the percentage difference between the acquisition price and the premerger price of the target firm.","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]}},"config":{"cssClass":""},"ref":"68832e5d-d986-4fc8-ab59-d660cccb860c"},{"type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"34b9d337-377e-4b00-8d1d-3ec8fd772200","nodes":[{"object":"inline","type":"reference-link","ref":"80844846-82b7-45b5-aa29-368b5c3cd7b6","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Table 22.2","marks":[]}],"data":{"reference":"9873ce10-44e1-11ed-8442-dbcbc27803ca"}},{"object":"text","text":" lists the average historical premium and market reaction to a takeover.","marks":[]},{"data":{"ref":"acfa4c7e-1a13-4450-ad20-d4f06e756585","stage":{"ref":"159c3909-a439-49c6-9124-4e62939e7778","sections":[{"ref":"e480493c-c952-4e95-9f50-924a5ad36475","rows":[{"ref":"e19f8b2e-83d6-44a1-8f57-5b7dbda1a3cd","columns":[{"ref":"a1260f6b-c2fe-4489-8e61-0937297c44bd","stageElements":[{"ref":"ed0bbbbc-e186-45ba-bd2c-4752d08b78f9","type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"button","ref":"4977b283-e1e9-45ef-a036-006d502b3c19","nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"8437b443-84a7-4222-b7fe-358d32841ea1","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"The original research done in the 1970s and 1980s documented that shareholders experience significant gains (between 20% and 30%) upon a successful takeover of their firms. More recent papers have found combined losses on the order of $240 billion in capitalization at the announcement of takeover bids. This finding appears to be driven by spectacular losses from some large takeovers of public targets, especially in the late 1990s.","marks":[]}],"data":{}}],"data":{}}]}}}]}]}]}]}},"nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"2","marks":[]}],"object":"inline","type":"footnote","ref":"c61ad8d7-a3e5-4549-b96d-4ec66966c328"},{"object":"text","text":" As the table shows, acquirers pay an average premium of 43% over the premerger price of the target. When a bid is announced, the target shareholders enjoy a gain of 15% on average in their stock price. Although acquirer shareholders see an ","marks":[]},{"object":"text","text":"average","marks":[{"type":"italic"}]},{"object":"text","text":" gain of 1%, in half of the transactions, the bidder price ","marks":[]},{"object":"text","text":"decreases","marks":[{"type":"italic"}]},{"object":"text","text":". These facts raise three important questions:","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]}},"config":{"cssClass":""},"ref":"33c4a7d9-8610-4c61-971a-d52d3ef44d5d"},{"type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"ordered-list","data":{"listOptionType":"1","startValue":1},"ref":"29174f5b-9c72-42db-aa6e-9484e9dbeca1","nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"list-item","data":{"direction":"auto"},"ref":"b7fa8f6d-5847-43a5-ad06-c6adbd99bc9b","nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"5dfb6ed5-923d-4a20-be07-c02eb3afe213","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Why do acquirers pay a premium over the market value for a target company?","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]},{"object":"block","type":"list-item","data":{"direction":"auto"},"ref":"ca7e9ce7-9d93-4679-9ecd-1b8cb17186f5","nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"5a4dacf5-7745-4b6a-a91c-72f67bdb7281","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Although the price of the target company rises on average upon the announcement of the takeover, why does it rise less than the premium offered by the acquirer?","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]},{"object":"block","type":"list-item","data":{"direction":"auto"},"ref":"dfdd036b-294e-4019-aeb2-2124e854e977","nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"4fd3423d-9a08-4b89-a5c2-f5b4c3fed7f8","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"If the transaction is a good idea, why does the acquirer not consistently experience a large price increase?","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]}]}]}},"config":{"cssClass":""},"ref":"2c2822b8-23ae-4a8d-81a9-682f049f1805"},{"type":"stage-element-table","config":{"activityLabel":"Table 22.2","instructions":"","tableCaptionText":"","activityTitle":"Average Acquisition Premium and Stock Price Reactions to Mergers","tableTitle":"","captions":"","credit":"<em>Source</em>: Data based on all U.S. deals from 1980 to 2005, as reported in <em>Handbook of Corporate Finance: Empirical Corporate Finance</em>, Vol. 2, <a class=\"xref\" href=\"m141_ch15.xhtml#ch15\">Chapter 15</a>, pp. 291&#x2013;430, B. E. Eckbo, ed., Elsevier/North-Holland Handbook of Finance Series, 2008."},"value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"data":{"id":"ch22table02"},"nodes":[{"data":{},"nodes":[{"data":{},"nodes":[{"data":{"colSpan":1,"rowSpan":1},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Premium Paid over","marks":[]}],"data":{}}],"object":"block","type":"table-header","ref":"c017a2f3-e013-4df4-a619-ab8e04d6724f"},{"data":{"colSpan":2,"rowSpan":1},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Announcement Price Reaction","marks":[]}],"data":{}}],"object":"block","type":"table-header","ref":"f990c8ff-4256-48f6-87e5-ef9f0cafeac3"}],"object":"block","type":"table-row","ref":"bbc8b2d9-b2d6-4dfa-9c26-d8ea3de96fbe"}],"object":"block","type":"table-head","ref":"4951db3d-cffa-4d28-b0b6-b4782db26ce1"},{"data":{},"nodes":[{"data":{},"nodes":[{"data":{"colSpan":1,"rowSpan":1},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Premerger Price","marks":[]}],"data":{}}],"object":"block","type":"table-data","ref":"980bf074-4aca-46d0-a111-95c2b9030048"},{"data":{"colSpan":1,"rowSpan":1},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Target","marks":[]}],"data":{}}],"object":"block","type":"table-data","ref":"f3a07b55-5db0-4634-b05f-6f0365f23ca1"},{"data":{"colSpan":1,"rowSpan":1},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Acquirer","marks":[]}],"data":{}}],"object":"block","type":"table-data","ref":"137c2489-8e36-496c-b9f2-6a0a056281d6"}],"object":"block","type":"table-row","ref":"8d105559-b608-4d67-8ce9-a14a5391af21"},{"data":{},"nodes":[{"data":{"colSpan":1,"rowSpan":1},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"43%","marks":[]}],"data":{}}],"object":"block","type":"table-data","ref":"f7a64cae-8f76-47bc-bb80-47a63cdb6067"},{"data":{"colSpan":1,"rowSpan":1},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"15%","marks":[]}],"data":{}}],"object":"block","type":"table-data","ref":"87c91155-425b-4e1d-811f-5ee685be6f1f"},{"data":{"colSpan":1,"rowSpan":1},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"1%","marks":[]}],"data":{}}],"object":"block","type":"table-data","ref":"41667f8e-c981-410f-896e-287983a4ae20"}],"object":"block","type":"table-row","ref":"fadc2f5c-99d0-4961-aedd-e6dd7640ab8e"}],"object":"block","type":"table-body","ref":"772dbe92-8f7b-4c56-897a-cd6929faaddc"}],"object":"block","type":"table","ref":"1aa4de8b-9dad-4495-966c-2d9edf34e5c4"}]}},"ref":"f22638ab-df78-4c88-ab07-abaa88212d08"},{"type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"f2d9e875-6a4f-4c8d-9552-6261059902c1","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Let’s start with the first question—why do acquirers pay a premium over market value? In fact, this question has two parts: (1) Why is the target worth a premium over the current market value? and (2) Even if the target is worth more than its premerger value, why do acquirers pay more than the premerger market price? In the next section, we answer the first part of this question. We delay the discussion of the second part until the end of the chapter, when we fully understand the mechanics of the takeover process.","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]}},"config":{"cssClass":""},"ref":"e16e91f7-e12c-46d5-9aba-b9746c45960b"}]}]}]},{"cssClass":"aside-group Sidebar_1Aside","rows":[{"columns":[{"stageElements":[{"type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"heading-two","ref":"0810b44d-3e6b-4900-a5d1-cbcc04df1ebc","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Concept Check","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]}},"config":{"cssClass":""},"ref":"443a8b26-2da7-43ff-bd20-ae11eba6987b"},{"type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"ordered-list","data":{"listOptionType":"1","startValue":3},"ref":"9a45e590-a57d-43d2-9d91-809a9a734195","nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"list-item","data":{"direction":"auto"},"ref":"016a7790-0cdc-49fa-a16a-6b9e1f0c88e7","nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"d28a28b8-7357-4727-804e-c99f04b8e7c8","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"On average, what happens to the target share price on the announcement of a takeover?","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]},{"object":"block","type":"list-item","data":{"direction":"auto"},"ref":"89ffbbe0-fa85-4160-8760-96b72d898deb","nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"27e586fc-7693-4b60-94f3-2446e2d30d28","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"On average, what happens to the acquirer share price on the announcement of a takeover?","marks":[]}]